{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775890058060,"sessionID":"ses_284b48ec7ffejtWYm3H6sVc1Hi","part":{"id":"prt_d7b4bc8530016KG8rDEW0G22KT","messageID":"msg_d7b4bb18b0018xDmFjiUa8ZPjL","sessionID":"ses_284b48ec7ffejtWYm3H6sVc1Hi","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-e3cd96f1578f437f8cfaa182d08a26ea","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # PCAP 分析器示例应用 Specification\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: [To be filled during spec definition]\n5: \n6: ## Requirements\n7: [To be filled during spec definition]\n\n(End of file - total 7 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# PCAP 分析器示例应用 Specification\n\n## Purpose\n[To be filled during spec definition]\n\n## Requirements\n[To be filled during spec definition]","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/spec.md","time":{"start":1775890058047,"end":1775890058059}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775890058064,"sessionID":"ses_284b48ec7ffejtWYm3H6sVc1Hi","part":{"id":"prt_d7b4bcb1d001fvOc8PkRVctLK4","messageID":"msg_d7b4bb18b0018xDmFjiUa8ZPjL","sessionID":"ses_284b48ec7ffejtWYm3H6sVc1Hi","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-a69736751ad0430194be201bc446d5b6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Specification — AR-037 PCAP 分析器示例应用\n2: \n3: ## AR Metadata\n4: - **AR ID**: AR-037\n5: - **Title**: PCAP 分析器示例应用\n6: - **Module**: example\n7: - **Language**: Python\n8: - **Size**: M\n9: - **Status**: Implementation Required\n10: \n11: ## Purpose\n12: \n13: Demonstrate AgentCube Python SDK usage by implementing a PCAP (packet capture) analyzer that uploads PCAP files to a Code Interpreter session, installs analysis libraries, executes analysis scripts, and returns insights about network traffic.\n14: \n15: ## Requirements\n16: \n17: ### Requirement: Environment setup for PCAP analysis\n18: \n19: The system SHALL prepare the Code Interpreter environment with necessary PCAP analysis libraries (scapy, pyshark, matplotlib, pandas) before performing any analysis.\n20: \n21: #### Scenario: Install scapy library\n22: \n23: - **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` session is initialized\n24: - **WHEN** the environment setup runs\n25: - **THEN** it SHALL execute `pip install scapy` and verify installation by importing scapy successfully\n26: \n27: #### Scenario: Install pyshark library\n28: \n29: - **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` session is initialized\n30: - **WHEN** the environment setup runs\n31: - **THEN** it SHALL execute `pip install pyshark` and verify installation by importing pyshark successfully\n32: \n33: #### Scenario: Install visualization libraries\n34: \n35: - **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` session is initialized\n36: - **WHEN** the environment setup runs\n37: - **THEN** it SHALL execute `pip install matplotlib pandas` for data visualization and analysis\n38: \n39: #### Scenario: Handle installation failures\n40: \n41: - **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` session is initialized\n42: - **WHEN** pip installation fails for any required library\n43: - **THEN** the system SHALL log the error and raise `CommandExecutionError` with details about which library failed to install\n44: \n45: ---\n46: \n47: ### Requirement: PCAP file upload\n48: \n49: The system SHALL provide functionality to upload local PCAP files to the Code Interpreter session for analysis.\n50: \n51: #### Scenario: Upload single PCAP file\n52: \n53: - **GIVEN** a local PCAP file exists at `/local/path/capture.pcap`\n54: - **WHEN** `upload_pcap_file(local_path, remote_path)` is called\n55: - **THEN** the file SHALL be uploaded to the remote Code Interpreter environment at the specified remote path\n56: \n57: #### Scenario: Upload multiple PCAP files\n58: \n59: - **GIVEN** multiple local PCAP files exist\n60: - **WHEN** `upload_pcap_files(file_list, remote_directory)` is called\n61: - **THEN** all files SHALL be uploaded to the remote directory and a success message SHALL confirm the count of uploaded files\n62: \n63: #### Scenario: Verify upload success\n64: \n65: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file was uploaded\n66: - **WHEN** `list_files()` is called on the remote path\n67: - **THEN** the uploaded file SHALL appear in the file listing\n68: \n69: #### Scenario: Handle invalid PCAP file path\n70: \n71: - **GIVEN** a local file path does not exist\n72: - **WHEN** `upload_pcap_file` is called with the invalid path\n73: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `FileNotFoundError` with the invalid path in the error message\n74: \n75: ---\n76: \n77: ### Requirement: Basic packet statistics\n78: \n79: The system SHALL provide functions to extract basic statistics from PCAP files including packet count, protocols, and time range.\n80: \n81: #### Scenario: Count total packets\n82: \n83: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded at `/remote/capture.pcap`\n84: - **WHEN** `analyze_packet_count(remote_path)` is called\n85: - **THEN** it SHALL return the total number of packets in the PCAP file\n86: \n87: #### Scenario: Identify protocols\n88: \n89: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n90: - **WHEN** `analyze_protocols(remote_path)` is called\n91: - **THEN** it SHALL return a dictionary mapping protocol names (TCP, UDP, ICMP, etc.) to packet counts\n92: \n93: #### Scenario: Calculate time range\n94: \n95: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n96: - **WHEN** `analyze_time_range(remote_path)` is called\n97: - **THEN** it SHALL return a tuple containing (start_timestamp, end_timestamp, duration_seconds)\n98: \n99: #### Scenario: Protocol distribution summary\n100: \n101: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n102: - **WHEN** `analyze_protocols(remote_path)` returns protocol counts\n103: - **THEN** the output SHALL include percentage distribution for each protocol\n104: \n105: ---\n106: \n107: ### Requirement: Top talkers analysis\n108: \n109: The system SHALL identify and rank top communicating IP addresses (both sources and destinations) by packet count and byte count.\n110: \n111: #### Scenario: Top source IPs by packet count\n112: \n113: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n114: - **WHEN** `analyze_top_source_ips(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n115: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (IP, packet_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n116: \n117: #### Scenario: Top destination IPs by packet count\n118: \n119: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n120: - **WHEN** `analyze_top_destination_ips(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n121: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (IP, packet_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n122: \n123: #### Scenario: Top IPs by byte count\n124: \n125: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n126: - **WHEN** `analyze_top_ips_by_bytes(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n127: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (IP, byte_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n128: \n129: #### Scenario: Bidirectional traffic summary\n130: \n131: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n132: - **WHEN** `analyze_bidirectional_traffic(remote_path)` is called\n133: - **THEN** it SHALL return a dictionary where keys are (source_ip, destination_ip) tuples and values are (packet_count, byte_count) tuples\n134: \n135: ---\n136: \n137: ### Requirement: Port analysis\n138: \n139: The system SHALL analyze network traffic by port numbers to identify commonly used services and ports.\n140: \n141: #### Scenario: Top source ports\n142: \n143: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n144: - **WHEN** `analyze_top_source_ports(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n145: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (port, packet_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n146: \n147: #### Scenario: Top destination ports\n148: \n149: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n150: - **WHEN** `analyze_top_destination_ports(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n151: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (port, packet_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n152: \n153: #### Scenario: Port-to-service mapping\n154: \n155: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n156: - **WHEN** `analyze_ports_with_services(remote_path)` is called\n157: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of (port, service_name, packet_count) tuples where well-known ports are mapped to common services (HTTP=80, HTTPS=443, DNS=53, etc.)\n158: \n159: #### Scenario: Filter by specific port\n160: \n161: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n162: - **WHEN** `filter_by_port(remote_path, port=443)` is called\n163: - **THEN** it SHALL return statistics for packets using only that destination port\n164: \n165: ---\n166: \n167: ### Requirement: Traffic visualization\n168: \n169: The system SHALL generate visualizations of PCAP analysis results including protocol distribution charts and time-series graphs.\n170: \n171: #### Scenario: Protocol distribution pie chart\n172: \n173: - **GIVEN** protocol analysis data is available\n174: - **WHEN** `visualize_protocol_distribution(protocol_data)` is called\n175: - **THEN** it SHALL generate a pie chart image file showing the percentage of each protocol and return the remote path to the image\n176: \n177: #### Scenario: Packets over time line chart\n178: \n179: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file is uploaded\n180: - **WHEN** `visualize_packets_over_time(remote_path)` is called\n181: - **THEN** it SHALL generate a line chart showing packet count per time interval and return the remote path to the image\n182: \n183: #### Scenario: Top IPs bar chart\n184: \n185: - **GIVEN** top IP analysis data is available\n186: - **WHEN** `visualize_top_ips(ip_data, title=\"Top IPs\")` is called\n187: - **THEN** it SHALL generate a horizontal bar chart showing top IPs and their packet counts and return the remote path to the image\n188: \n189: #### Scenario: Download visualization image\n190: \n191: - **GIVEN** a visualization image was generated at `/remote/protocol_distribution.png`\n192: - **WHEN** `download_file(remote_path, local_path)` is called\n193: - **THEN** the image SHALL be downloaded to the specified local path\n194: \n195: ---\n196: \n197: ### Requirement: HTTP traffic analysis\n198: \n199: The system SHALL extract and analyze HTTP-specific information including URLs, user agents, and status codes.\n200: \n201: #### Scenario: Extract HTTP requests\n202: \n203: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing HTTP traffic is uploaded\n204: - **WHEN** `analyze_http_requests(remote_path)` is called\n205: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of dictionaries containing (method, url, host, user_agent) for each HTTP request\n206: \n207: #### Scenario: Extract HTTP responses\n208: \n209: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing HTTP traffic is uploaded\n210: - **WHEN** `analyze_http_responses(remote_path)` is called\n211: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of dictionaries containing (status_code, content_type, response_length) for each HTTP response\n212: \n213: #### Scenario: Count HTTP status codes\n214: \n215: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing HTTP traffic is uploaded\n216: - **WHEN** `analyze_http_status_codes(remote_path)` is called\n217: - **THEN** it SHALL return a dictionary mapping status codes (200, 404, 500, etc.) to occurrence counts\n218: \n219: #### Scenario: Top HTTP hosts\n220: \n221: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing HTTP traffic is uploaded\n222: - **WHEN** `analyze_top_http_hosts(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n223: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (host, request_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n224: \n225: ---\n226: \n227: ### Requirement: DNS traffic analysis\n228: \n229: The system SHALL extract and analyze DNS queries and responses to identify queried domains and response types.\n230: \n231: #### Scenario: Extract DNS queries\n232: \n233: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing DNS traffic is uploaded\n234: - **WHEN** `analyze_dns_queries(remote_path)` is called\n235: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of queried domain names\n236: \n237: #### Scenario: Count top queried domains\n238: \n239: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing DNS traffic is uploaded\n240: - **WHEN** `analyze_top_dns_domains(remote_path, limit=10)` is called\n241: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of up to 10 (domain, query_count) tuples sorted in descending order\n242: \n243: #### Scenario: DNS response types\n244: \n245: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing DNS traffic is uploaded\n246: - **WHEN** `analyze_dns_response_types(remote_path)` is called\n247: - **THEN** it SHALL return a dictionary mapping DNS record types (A, AAAA, CNAME, MX, etc.) to occurrence counts\n248: \n249: #### Scenario: DNS resolution failures\n250: \n251: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file containing DNS traffic is uploaded\n252: - **WHEN** `analyze_dns_failures(remote_path)` is called\n253: - **THEN** it SHALL return a list of domain names that received NXDOMAIN or SERVFAIL responses\n254: \n255: ---\n256: \n257: ### Requirement: Comprehensive analysis report\n258: \n259: The system SHALL generate a comprehensive markdown or HTML report combining all analysis results.\n260: \n261: #### Scenario: Generate markdown report\n262: \n263: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file has been fully analyzed\n264: - **WHEN** `generate_report(analysis_results, output_path, format=\"markdown\")` is called\n265: - **THEN** it SHALL create a markdown file at the specified output path containing sections for basic statistics, top talkers, port analysis, HTTP analysis, DNS analysis, and embedded visualization images\n266: \n267: #### Scenario: Generate HTML report\n268: \n269: - **GIVEN** a PCAP file has been fully analyzed\n270: - **WHEN** `generate_report(analysis_results, output_path, format=\"html\")` is called\n271: - **THEN** it SHALL create an HTML file at the specified output path with styled sections and embedded visualization images\n272: \n273: #### Scenario: Download complete report\n274: \n275: - **GIVEN** a report was generated at `/remote/report.md`\n276: - **WHEN** `download_file(remote_path, local_path)` is called\n277: - **THEN** the complete report file SHALL be downloaded to the specified local path\n278: \n279: #### Scenario: Report includes execution metadata\n280: \n281: - **GIVEN** a report is being generated\n282: - **WHEN** the report is created\n283: - **THEN** it SHALL include metadata such as file name, analysis timestamp, and total execution time\n284: \n285: ---\n286: \n287: ### Requirement: Example usage script\n288: \n289: The system SHALL provide a complete example script demonstrating end-to-end usage of the PCAP analyzer with the AgentCube SDK.\n290: \n291: #### Scenario: Basic usage example\n292: \n293: - **GIVEN** the example script `pcap_analyzer_example.py` exists\n294: - **WHEN** the script is executed with a sample PCAP file\n295: - **THEN** it SHALL initialize a `CodeInterpreterClient`, upload the PCAP file, run all analyses, generate a report, and download results\n296: \n297: #### Scenario: Example with custom configuration\n298: \n299: - **GIVEN** the example script supports configuration parameters\n300: - **WHEN** run with custom `name`, `namespace`, and `ttl` arguments\n301: - **THEN** the Code Interpreter session SHALL be created with the specified parameters\n302: \n303: #### Scenario: Example handles cleanup\n304: \n305: - **GIVEN** the example script completes analysis\n306: - **WHEN** the script exits (either successfully or with error)\n307: - **THEN** it SHALL properly clean up by stopping the Code Interpreter session via context manager\n308: \n309: #### Scenario: Example error handling\n310: \n311: - **GIVEN** the example script encounters an error during analysis\n312: - **WHEN** an exception occurs\n313: - **THEN** it SHALL log the error, display a user-friendly message, and exit gracefully\n314: \n315: ---\n316: \n317: ### Requirement: Code Interpreter session management\n318: \n319: The system SHALL properly manage Code Interpreter sessions including initialization, reuse, and cleanup.\n320: \n321: #### Scenario: Reuse existing session\n322: \n323: - **GIVEN** a `session_id` is provided to the `CodeInterpreterClient`\n324: - **WHEN** the client is initialized\n325: - **THEN** it SHALL connect to the existing session without creating a new one\n326: \n327: #### Scenario: Session cleanup on completion\n328: \n329: - **GIVEN** a PCAP analysis completes successfully\n330: - **WHEN** the analysis script exits the context manager\n331: - **THEN** the session SHALL be stopped and cleaned up automatically\n332: \n333: #### Scenario: Session cleanup on error\n334: \n335: - **GIVEN** a PCAP analysis encounters an error\n336: - **WHEN** the analysis script exits the context manager with an exception\n337: - **THEN** the session SHALL still be stopped and cleaned up automatically\n338: \n339: #### Scenario: Verbose logging\n340: \n341: - **GIVEN** `verbose=True` is set on the `CodeInterpreterClient`\n342: - **WHEN** operations are performed\n343: - **THEN** detailed log messages SHALL be output for each operation (upload, execute, download)\n344: \n345: ---\n346: \n347: ### Requirement: Performance optimization\n348: \n349: The system SHALL handle large PCAP files efficiently with appropriate timeout and resource management.\n350: \n351: #### Scenario: Large file timeout handling\n352: \n353: - **GIVEN** a large PCAP file (>100MB) is being analyzed\n354: - **WHEN** analysis operations are executed\n355: - **THEN** appropriate timeouts SHALL be used for long-running commands and the system SHALL handle timeouts gracefully\n356: \n357: #### Scenario: Chunked processing for very large files\n358: \n359: - **GIVEN** a very large PCAP file (>1GB) is being analyzed\n360: - **WHEN** packet analysis runs\n361: - **THEN** the system SHALL process the file in chunks to avoid memory exhaustion\n362: \n363: #### Scenario: Progress reporting for long operations\n364: \n365: - **GIVEN** a long-running analysis is in progress\n366: - **WHEN** the operation takes more than 10 seconds\n367: - **THEN** the system SHALL log progress messages at regular intervals\n368: \n369: #### Scenario: Resource cleanup after analysis\n370: \n371: - **GIVEN** analysis of a large file completes\n372: - **WHEN** the analysis script finishes\n373: - **THEN** temporary files and resources SHALL be cleaned up in the remote environment\n374: \n375: ---\n376: \n377: ## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n378: \n379: 1. ✅ Code Interpreter environment setup with required libraries\n380: 2. ✅ PCAP file upload functionality (single and multiple files)\n381: 3. ✅ Basic packet statistics (count, protocols, time range)\n382: 4. ✅ Top talkers analysis (source/destination IPs by packet and byte count)\n383: 5. ✅ Port analysis with service mapping\n384: 6. ✅ Traffic visualization (protocol distribution, time series, top IPs)\n385: 7. ✅ HTTP traffic analysis (requests, responses, status codes, hosts)\n386: 8. ✅ DNS traffic analysis (queries, domains, response types, failures)\n387: 9. ✅ Comprehensive report generation (markdown and HTML)\n388: 10. ✅ Example usage script with proper configuration and cleanup\n389: 11. ✅ Code Interpreter session management (reuse, cleanup, logging)\n390: 12. ✅ Performance optimization for large files (timeouts, chunking, progress)\n391: \n392: ---\n393: \n394: ## Dependencies\n395: \n396: - `agentcube-sdk>=0.0.10` (CodeInterpreterClient)\n397: - `scapy>=2.5.0` (PCAP parsing)\n398: - `pyshark>=0.6` (Wireshark-compatible parsing)\n399: - `matplotlib>=3.7.0` (visualization)\n400: - `pandas>=2.0.0` (data analysis)\n401: - Python >=3.10\n402: \n403: ---\n404: \n405: ## References\n406: \n407: - Base Design: `python-sdk/design.md`\n408: - Base Specification: `python-sdk/spec.md`\n409: - AR: AR-037 — PCAP 分析器示例应用\n\n(End of file - total 409 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Specification — AR-037 PCAP 分析器示例应用\n\n## AR Metadata\n- **AR ID**: AR-037\n- **Title**: PCAP 分析器示例应用\n- **Module**: example\n- **Language**: Python\n- **Size**: M\n- **Status**: Implementation Required\n\n## Purpose\n\nDemonstrate AgentCube Python SDK usage by implementing a PCAP (packet capture) analyzer that uploads PCAP files to a Code Interpreter session, installs analysis libraries, executes analysis scripts, and returns insights about network traffic.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Environment setup for PCAP analysis\n\nThe system SHALL prepare the Code Interpreter environment with necessary PCAP analysis libraries (scapy, pyshark, matplotlib, pandas) before performing any analysis.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-037/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775890058050,"end":1775890058061}}}}
